tional pressures </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> inextricably linked to the broken funding model for emergency services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The FTN’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">benchmarking reports have shown that for the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">majority of surveyed trusts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the costs of providing A&amp;E services exceeds the income received</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">When this measure is extended to encompass all emergency admissions to hospital</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">becomes clear that the funding pattern for emergency care is simply not susta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Of the 26 trusts we surveyed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> recently</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, all but one (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a trust delivering specialist care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> was operating emergency admission services at a deficit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">roviders of A&amp;E services are treat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> unplanned admissions to hospital at a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">loss</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is exacerbated by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the marginal rate for emergency admissions and non-payment of readmissions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">through which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">providers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are penalised for factor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> beyond their control</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At the same</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">time trusts are losing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> elective income as operations are cancelled or reschedu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">led because of the demand for emergency activity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, with this activity being made up through expensive premium </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">operating </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sessions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Over winter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> trusts are essentially losing elective activity at 100% and being paid for emergency activity at only 30% of costs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Every cancelled operation has a human cost, and ultimately this pattern of funding will lead to services for the most critical patients be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">coming clinically and financially unsustainable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We welcomed the Health Committee’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> July</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> call for changes to the 30% marginal rate policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which has been endorsed by the recent NAO report into emergency admissions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since then, al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">though the governance a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nd transparency of the policy have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">significantly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improved</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> its fundamental nature</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has not changed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Trusts are losing over £300 million each year in emergency care funding, with individual hospitals losing up to a further £3.5 million through the non-payme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nt of readmissions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Even as we develop new systems for paying for emergency services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the service cannot be allowed to run down to the point where it is impossible to successfully transform care delivery models.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span sty